"{\"value\":{\"mdx\":\"# ZCAM vs Other Approaches\\n\\nThere already exist numerous technologies in the authenticity and verifiability of images space. These solutions, however, solve for slightly different problem spaces and provide varying levels of functionality.\\n\\n:::info\\nZCAM provides a complete solution for mobile photo authenticity verification. It combines hardware-backed attestation, optional zero-knowledge proofs, embedded verification data, and simple verification output (verified/not verified) into a single integrated system designed specifically for human-taken photos on mobile devices.\\n:::\\n\\nBelow is a feature comparison showing what each approach provides. See further sections below for more details on other tools and advantages that ZCAM can provide.\\n\\n## Comparison Table\\n\\n| Approach | Hardware Attestation | ZK Proofs | Embedded Verification | User-friendly Output | Camera Photos | Use Case |\\n|----------|---------------------|-----------|---------------------|---------------|--------------|----------|\\n| **ZCAM** | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | Complete mobile photo authenticity solution |\\n| **C2PA (generic)** | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ | Edit history tracking, content provenance |\\n| **Physical Camera** | ❓ | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ | For C2PA-compatible cameras, note only some cameras support hardware-backed signing |\\n| **JPEG Trust** | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | Trust evaluation framework (leverages C2PA) |\\n| **SynthID** | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | AI watermarking and detection |\\n| **AI Content Marking** | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | AI-generated content marking (watermarking or C2PA) |\\n\\n## Other tooling\\n\\n### C2PA\\n\\nThe C2PA content credential standard aims to create a *verifiable history* of a given image. \\n\\nNote, it is *not* specific to \\\"authentic\\\" images, i.e. it can be applied to both camera-captured pictures, as well as AI-generated images. It creates a specification for attaching contextual metadata as an image evolves over time. For example, an initial image can be captured using a camera or generated using AI. An initial *C2PA Manifest* is attached to the image indicating its origin. Thereafter, as edits are made (using C2PA-compatible editors), new manifests are attached indicating the edits made (e.g. cropping, brightness balancing, etc.). All of these manifests are signed using public key cryptography.\\n\\n**Key Differences from ZCAM:**\\n- C2PA doesn't require hardware attestation. any signing key can be used to sign attestations.\\n- C2PA focuses on edit history, while ZCAM focuses on capture authenticity\\n- ZCAM uses C2PA as the container format but adds hardware-backed guarantees\\n- C2PA is a more flexible, generic tooling for attaching historical metadata to an image, ZCAM focuses on proving authenticity of an iamge.\\n\\nMore technical information can be found in the [How it Works](/overview/how_it_works) section under C2PA.\\n\\n### JPEG Trust\\n\\nJPEG Trust provides a framework for evaluating the trustworthiness of an image. It is actually compatible with C2PA, and relies *on* the data encoded in C2PA manifests. \\n\\nThe main value here is the ability to create trust *profiles* and *evaluators* that leverage the bound data, which allows users to conclude the authenticity for a given photo.\\n\\n**Key Differences from ZCAM:**\\n- JPEG Trust is an evaluation framework, not a capture/verification system\\n- It can work with ZCAM-generated C2PA manifests\\n- Focuses on trust scoring rather than cryptographic verification\\n\\n### SynthID\\n\\nSynthID, developed by Google, is an invisible watermark framework that can embed data into an image in a more resilient format. Solutions that use the JUMBF metadata are susceptible to getting the metadata stripped, the photo getting edited/cropped, etc. The actual embedded data is based on an AI model, and can later be read and analyzed by another model that decides whether a photo is AI-generated or not.\\n\\n**Key Differences from ZCAM:**\\n- SynthID focuses on AI detection, ZCAM focuses on authenticity verification\\n- ZCAM provides cryptographic guarantees, SynthID provides probabilistic detection\\n\\n### IPTC Photo Metadata\\n\\nThe IPTC Photo Metadata simply defines standardized nomenclature and labeling for the aforementioned protocols. It's a metadata standard rather than a verification system.\\n\\n**Key Differences from ZCAM:**\\n- IPTC is a metadata format, not a verification system\\n- Can be used alongside ZCAM for standardized metadata fields\\n- No cryptographic guarantees or hardware attestation\\n\\n### AI Content Marking\\n\\nSeveral companies provide solutions for marking AI-generated content, using different approaches:\\n\\n- **Meta Watermarking**: Meta adds watermarks specifically to AI-generated content. These watermarks are meant to be durable, handling cropping and edit actions, etc.\\n- **OpenAI C2PA**: OpenAI (e.g. ChatGPT) generated images include C2PA manifests indicating they were generated using DALL-E and on ChatGPT. This is also included in Azure's OpenAI service.\\n\\n**Key Differences from ZCAM:**\\n- These solutions focus on marking AI-generated content, while ZCAM verifies authentic human-captured photos\\n- No hardware attestation in these implementations\\n- Different goals: provenance/marking for AI content vs. authenticity verification for human-captured photos\\n- Watermark-based (Meta) or C2PA-based (OpenAI) rather than hardware-backed cryptographic verification\\n\\n## When to Use ZCAM\\n\\nZCAM is the right choice when you need:\\n\\n- **Hardware-backed authenticity**: Guarantees that photos were taken on a specific device\\n- **Cryptographic verification**: Strong cryptographic proofs rather than probabilistic detection\\n- **Mobile-first**: Designed specifically for iOS (and planned Android) mobile apps\\n- **Simple verification**: Easy-to-use API that returns verified/not verified without requiring manifest parsing\\n- **Complete solution**: End-to-end flow from capture to verification with optional ZK proof integration\\n\\nConsider other approaches when:\\n\\n- You need to mark AI-generated content (use SynthID or AI Content Marking solutions)\\n- You want a general-purpose edit history system (use generic C2PA)\\n- You need watermarking resilient to heavy editing (use SynthID)\\n- You're working with non-mobile platforms (use C2PA or other standards)\\n\\n\",\"document\":[{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#zcam-vs-other-approaches\",\"html\":\"</header>\\n<p>There already exist numerous technologies in the authenticity and verifiability of images space. These solutions, however, solve for slightly different problem spaces and provide varying levels of functionality.</p>\\n<aside data-callout=\\\"info\\\"><p>ZCAM provides a complete solution for mobile photo authenticity verification. It combines hardware-backed attestation, optional zero-knowledge proofs, embedded verification data, and simple verification output (verified/not verified) into a single integrated system designed specifically for human-taken photos on mobile devices.</p></aside>\\n<p>Below is a feature comparison showing what each approach provides. See further sections below for more details on other tools and advantages that ZCAM can provide.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#zcam-vs-other-approaches\",\"isPage\":true,\"text\":\"\\nThere already exist numerous technologies in the authenticity and verifiability of images space. These solutions, however, solve for slightly different problem spaces and provide varying levels of functionality.\\nZCAM provides a complete solution for mobile photo authenticity verification. It combines hardware-backed attestation, optional zero-knowledge proofs, embedded verification data, and simple verification output (verified/not verified) into a single integrated system designed specifically for human-taken photos on mobile devices.\\nBelow is a feature comparison showing what each approach provides. See further sections below for more details on other tools and advantages that ZCAM can provide.\\n\",\"title\":\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\",\"titles\":[]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#comparison-table\",\"html\":\"\\n<table><thead><tr><th>Approach</th><th>Hardware Attestation</th><th>ZK Proofs</th><th>Embedded Verification</th><th>User-friendly Output</th><th>Camera Photos</th><th>Use Case</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>ZCAM</strong></td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>Complete mobile photo authenticity solution</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C2PA (generic)</strong></td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>Edit history tracking, content provenance</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Physical Camera</strong></td><td>❓</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>For C2PA-compatible cameras, note only some cameras support hardware-backed signing</td></tr><tr><td><strong>JPEG Trust</strong></td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>✅</td><td>Trust evaluation framework (leverages C2PA)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>SynthID</strong></td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td>AI watermarking and detection</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AI Content Marking</strong></td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td>✅</td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td>AI-generated content marking (watermarking or C2PA)</td></tr></tbody></table>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#comparison-table\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nApproachHardware AttestationZK ProofsEmbedded VerificationUser-friendly OutputCamera PhotosUse CaseZCAM✅✅✅✅✅Complete mobile photo authenticity solutionC2PA (generic)❌❌✅❌✅Edit history tracking, content provenancePhysical Camera❓❌✅❌✅For C2PA-compatible cameras, note only some cameras support hardware-backed signingJPEG Trust❌❌✅✅✅Trust evaluation framework (leverages C2PA)SynthID❌❌✅❌❌AI watermarking and detectionAI Content Marking❌❌✅❌❌AI-generated content marking (watermarking or C2PA)\\n\",\"title\":\"Comparison Table\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#other-tooling\",\"html\":\"\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#other-tooling\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\n\",\"title\":\"Other tooling\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#c2pa\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>The C2PA content credential standard aims to create a <em>verifiable history</em> of a given image.</p>\\n<p>Note, it is <em>not</em> specific to &quot;authentic&quot; images, i.e. it can be applied to both camera-captured pictures, as well as AI-generated images. It creates a specification for attaching contextual metadata as an image evolves over time. For example, an initial image can be captured using a camera or generated using AI. An initial <em>C2PA Manifest</em> is attached to the image indicating its origin. Thereafter, as edits are made (using C2PA-compatible editors), new manifests are attached indicating the edits made (e.g. cropping, brightness balancing, etc.). All of these manifests are signed using public key cryptography.</p>\\n<strong>Key Differences from ZCAM:</strong>\\n<ul>\\n<li>C2PA doesn&#x27;t require hardware attestation. any signing key can be used to sign attestations.</li>\\n<li>C2PA focuses on edit history, while ZCAM focuses on capture authenticity</li>\\n<li>ZCAM uses C2PA as the container format but adds hardware-backed guarantees</li>\\n<li>C2PA is a more flexible, generic tooling for attaching historical metadata to an image, ZCAM focuses on proving authenticity of an iamge.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>More technical information can be found in the <a href=\\\"/overview/how_it_works\\\">How it Works</a> section under C2PA.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#c2pa\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThe C2PA content credential standard aims to create a verifiable history of a given image.\\nNote, it is not specific to &quot;authentic&quot; images, i.e. it can be applied to both camera-captured pictures, as well as AI-generated images. It creates a specification for attaching contextual metadata as an image evolves over time. For example, an initial image can be captured using a camera or generated using AI. An initial C2PA Manifest is attached to the image indicating its origin. Thereafter, as edits are made (using C2PA-compatible editors), new manifests are attached indicating the edits made (e.g. cropping, brightness balancing, etc.). All of these manifests are signed using public key cryptography.\\nKey Differences from ZCAM:\\n\\nC2PA doesn&#x27;t require hardware attestation. any signing key can be used to sign attestations.\\nC2PA focuses on edit history, while ZCAM focuses on capture authenticity\\nZCAM uses C2PA as the container format but adds hardware-backed guarantees\\nC2PA is a more flexible, generic tooling for attaching historical metadata to an image, ZCAM focuses on proving authenticity of an iamge.\\n\\nMore technical information can be found in the How it Works section under C2PA.\\n\",\"title\":\"C2PA\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\",\"Other tooling\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#jpeg-trust\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>JPEG Trust provides a framework for evaluating the trustworthiness of an image. It is actually compatible with C2PA, and relies <em>on</em> the data encoded in C2PA manifests.</p>\\n<p>The main value here is the ability to create trust <em>profiles</em> and <em>evaluators</em> that leverage the bound data, which allows users to conclude the authenticity for a given photo.</p>\\n<strong>Key Differences from ZCAM:</strong>\\n<ul>\\n<li>JPEG Trust is an evaluation framework, not a capture/verification system</li>\\n<li>It can work with ZCAM-generated C2PA manifests</li>\\n<li>Focuses on trust scoring rather than cryptographic verification</li>\\n</ul>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#jpeg-trust\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nJPEG Trust provides a framework for evaluating the trustworthiness of an image. It is actually compatible with C2PA, and relies on the data encoded in C2PA manifests.\\nThe main value here is the ability to create trust profiles and evaluators that leverage the bound data, which allows users to conclude the authenticity for a given photo.\\nKey Differences from ZCAM:\\n\\nJPEG Trust is an evaluation framework, not a capture/verification system\\nIt can work with ZCAM-generated C2PA manifests\\nFocuses on trust scoring rather than cryptographic verification\\n\\n\",\"title\":\"JPEG Trust\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\",\"Other tooling\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#synthid\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>SynthID, developed by Google, is an invisible watermark framework that can embed data into an image in a more resilient format. Solutions that use the JUMBF metadata are susceptible to getting the metadata stripped, the photo getting edited/cropped, etc. The actual embedded data is based on an AI model, and can later be read and analyzed by another model that decides whether a photo is AI-generated or not.</p>\\n<strong>Key Differences from ZCAM:</strong>\\n<ul>\\n<li>SynthID focuses on AI detection, ZCAM focuses on authenticity verification</li>\\n<li>ZCAM provides cryptographic guarantees, SynthID provides probabilistic detection</li>\\n</ul>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#synthid\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nSynthID, developed by Google, is an invisible watermark framework that can embed data into an image in a more resilient format. Solutions that use the JUMBF metadata are susceptible to getting the metadata stripped, the photo getting edited/cropped, etc. The actual embedded data is based on an AI model, and can later be read and analyzed by another model that decides whether a photo is AI-generated or not.\\nKey Differences from ZCAM:\\n\\nSynthID focuses on AI detection, ZCAM focuses on authenticity verification\\nZCAM provides cryptographic guarantees, SynthID provides probabilistic detection\\n\\n\",\"title\":\"SynthID\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\",\"Other tooling\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#iptc-photo-metadata\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>The IPTC Photo Metadata simply defines standardized nomenclature and labeling for the aforementioned protocols. It&#x27;s a metadata standard rather than a verification system.</p>\\n<strong>Key Differences from ZCAM:</strong>\\n<ul>\\n<li>IPTC is a metadata format, not a verification system</li>\\n<li>Can be used alongside ZCAM for standardized metadata fields</li>\\n<li>No cryptographic guarantees or hardware attestation</li>\\n</ul>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#iptc-photo-metadata\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThe IPTC Photo Metadata simply defines standardized nomenclature and labeling for the aforementioned protocols. It&#x27;s a metadata standard rather than a verification system.\\nKey Differences from ZCAM:\\n\\nIPTC is a metadata format, not a verification system\\nCan be used alongside ZCAM for standardized metadata fields\\nNo cryptographic guarantees or hardware attestation\\n\\n\",\"title\":\"IPTC Photo Metadata\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\",\"Other tooling\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#ai-content-marking\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>Several companies provide solutions for marking AI-generated content, using different approaches:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Meta Watermarking</strong>: Meta adds watermarks specifically to AI-generated content. These watermarks are meant to be durable, handling cropping and edit actions, etc.</li>\\n<li><strong>OpenAI C2PA</strong>: OpenAI (e.g. ChatGPT) generated images include C2PA manifests indicating they were generated using DALL-E and on ChatGPT. This is also included in Azure&#x27;s OpenAI service.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<strong>Key Differences from ZCAM:</strong>\\n<ul>\\n<li>These solutions focus on marking AI-generated content, while ZCAM verifies authentic human-captured photos</li>\\n<li>No hardware attestation in these implementations</li>\\n<li>Different goals: provenance/marking for AI content vs. authenticity verification for human-captured photos</li>\\n<li>Watermark-based (Meta) or C2PA-based (OpenAI) rather than hardware-backed cryptographic verification</li>\\n</ul>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#ai-content-marking\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nSeveral companies provide solutions for marking AI-generated content, using different approaches:\\n\\nMeta Watermarking: Meta adds watermarks specifically to AI-generated content. These watermarks are meant to be durable, handling cropping and edit actions, etc.\\nOpenAI C2PA: OpenAI (e.g. ChatGPT) generated images include C2PA manifests indicating they were generated using DALL-E and on ChatGPT. This is also included in Azure&#x27;s OpenAI service.\\n\\nKey Differences from ZCAM:\\n\\nThese solutions focus on marking AI-generated content, while ZCAM verifies authentic human-captured photos\\nNo hardware attestation in these implementations\\nDifferent goals: provenance/marking for AI content vs. authenticity verification for human-captured photos\\nWatermark-based (Meta) or C2PA-based (OpenAI) rather than hardware-backed cryptographic verification\\n\\n\",\"title\":\"AI Content Marking\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\",\"Other tooling\"]},{\"href\":\"/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches#when-to-use-zcam\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>ZCAM is the right choice when you need:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Hardware-backed authenticity</strong>: Guarantees that photos were taken on a specific device</li>\\n<li><strong>Cryptographic verification</strong>: Strong cryptographic proofs rather than probabilistic detection</li>\\n<li><strong>Mobile-first</strong>: Designed specifically for iOS (and planned Android) mobile apps</li>\\n<li><strong>Simple verification</strong>: Easy-to-use API that returns verified/not verified without requiring manifest parsing</li>\\n<li><strong>Complete solution</strong>: End-to-end flow from capture to verification with optional ZK proof integration</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Consider other approaches when:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>You need to mark AI-generated content (use SynthID or AI Content Marking solutions)</li>\\n<li>You want a general-purpose edit history system (use generic C2PA)</li>\\n<li>You need watermarking resilient to heavy editing (use SynthID)</li>\\n<li>You&#x27;re working with non-mobile platforms (use C2PA or other standards)</li>\\n</ul>\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/overview/comparisons_to_other_approaches.mdx#when-to-use-zcam\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nZCAM is the right choice when you need:\\n\\nHardware-backed authenticity: Guarantees that photos were taken on a specific device\\nCryptographic verification: Strong cryptographic proofs rather than probabilistic detection\\nMobile-first: Designed specifically for iOS (and planned Android) mobile apps\\nSimple verification: Easy-to-use API that returns verified/not verified without requiring manifest parsing\\nComplete solution: End-to-end flow from capture to verification with optional ZK proof integration\\n\\nConsider other approaches when:\\n\\nYou need to mark AI-generated content (use SynthID or AI Content Marking solutions)\\nYou want a general-purpose edit history system (use generic C2PA)\\nYou need watermarking resilient to heavy editing (use SynthID)\\nYou&#x27;re working with non-mobile platforms (use C2PA or other standards)\\n\",\"title\":\"When to Use ZCAM\",\"titles\":[\"ZCAM vs Other Approaches\"]}]}}"
